+# Idea Discovery Report
+
+**Direction**: vLLM-first pre-study for MoE load balancing on DeepSeek-V2-Lite matrix4
+**Date**: 2026-04-17
+**Pipeline**: research-lit -> idea-creator -> novelty-check -> research-review -> research-refine-pipeline
+
+## Executive Summary
+
+The recommended idea is a **trace-grounded end-to-end CV response study** for `vLLM` on `DeepSeek-V2-Lite` matrix4, not a new balancing algorithm yet. The current evidence says the key uncertainty is metric choice and serving regime: the single-layer MoE kernel benchmark is almost flat from physical CV `0.05` to `0.20`, but real serving traces show materially larger **decode-only** imbalance and the observed benefit or harm of `EPLB` depends on whether imbalance is summarized at the layer, whole-model, or decode-only level.
+
+This study is worth doing because it answers both target questions directly. It establishes whether larger routing/load CV causes meaningful end-to-end degradation in the real `vLLM` engine, and whether real downstream workloads can naturally or scheduler-inducingly reach the relevant imbalance regime. If the answer is "no", the team should stop before spending time on a new balancer. If the answer is "yes", the study produces the exact target regime and metrics needed for a follow-on optimization.
+
+## Literature Landscape
+
+### What the literature already says
+
+- `DeepSeek-V2` frames `DeepSeekMoE` as an efficient sparse architecture, but does not claim that training-time balance guarantees serving-time balance. Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2405.04434
+- `Auxiliary-Loss-Free Load Balancing Strategy for Mixture-of-Experts` is a training-time balancing method. It improves expert load during training, but does not solve serving-time scheduling or engine-level imbalance. Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2408.15664
+- `vLLM`'s own EP documentation explicitly states that MoE token distributions can be highly skewed in practice and exposes `EPLB` plus `num_redundant_experts` as a systems remedy, with a memory overhead tradeoff. Source: https://docs.vllm.ai/en/v0.12.0/serving/expert_parallel_deployment/
+- `Least-Loaded Expert Parallelism` argues that even well-trained MoEs can show strong post-training and inference imbalance, and reports up to `5x` speedup and `4x` peak-memory reduction under extreme imbalance. Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2601.17111
+- `Efficient MoE Serving in the Memory-Bound Regime: Balance Activated Experts, Not Tokens` argues that token balancing can be the wrong target for decode-heavy memory-bound serving, and reports `11-22%` decode-latency reductions over `EPLB` on `vLLM`. Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2512.09277
+- `DeepEP` is a communication library, not a proof that routing imbalance is or is not the dominant engine bottleneck. Source: https://github.com/deepseek-ai/DeepEP
+
+### What is still missing
+
+- A **vLLM-specific**, **DeepSeek-V2-Lite-specific**, **matrix4-specific** answer to whether realistic engine traces actually enter the imbalance regime where a new balancing policy matters.
+- A principled bridge between three different summaries that currently tell different stories:
+  - weighted per-layer CV
+  - whole-model per-step CV
+  - decode-only whole-model CV
+- A causal curve from **real trace imbalance** to **end-to-end latency and throughput**, rather than another isolated kernel sweep.
+
+## Current Evidence
+
+### Local measurements already available
+
+From `/home/lzy/eval/vllm_deepseek_v2_lite_matrix4/summary.csv`:
+
+| Engine | Dataset | Case | Total token throughput |
+|---|---|---|---:|
+| vLLM | multifieldqa_en | `nochunk_noeplb` | 5389.44 |
+| vLLM | multifieldqa_en | `nochunk_eplb` | 4099.42 |
+| vLLM | multifieldqa_en | `chunk_noeplb` | 5424.94 |
+| vLLM | multifieldqa_en | `chunk_eplb` | 3503.73 |
+
+From `/home/lzy/eval/vllm_kernel_cv_sweep/cv_sweep_summary.csv`:
+
+| Synthetic physical CV | Mean tokens/s | Mean max-rank step ms |
+|---:|---:|---:|
+| 0.05 | 481703.15 | 17.0069 |
+| 0.10 | 482224.84 | 16.9886 |
+| 0.15 | 481988.27 | 16.9972 |
+| 0.20 | 482818.16 | 16.9678 |
+
+Inference from the local kernel data: **the current single-layer synthetic benchmark is almost flat across the tested CV range**. That does not prove there is no headroom in `vLLM`; it proves only that this kernel-only setup is insufficient to answer the end-to-end question.
+
+### Metric reconciliation from local trace analysis
+
+Inference from local trace analysis performed in this run:
+
+- On the existing **weighted per-layer CV** summary, `vLLM` `multifieldqa_en` is around `0.07-0.094`.
+- On the same per-layer summary, `SGLang` is not actually near zero; depending on workload and case it can also reach roughly `0.07-0.14`.
+- On **whole-model weighted CV across all tokens**, the numbers compress sharply:
+  - `vLLM` `multifieldqa_en`: about `0.0209-0.0353`
+  - `SGLang` `multifieldqa_en`: about `0.0196-0.0295`
+  - `SGLang` `2wikimqa`: about `0.0168-0.0296`
+  - `SGLang` `qasper`: about `0.0195-0.0303`
+- On **decode-only whole-model CV**, imbalance is much larger:
+  - `vLLM` `multifieldqa_en`: about `0.115-0.133`
+  - `SGLang` `multifieldqa_en`: about `0.079-0.092`
+  - `SGLang` `2wikimqa`: about `0.086-0.097`
+  - `SGLang` `qasper`: about `0.097-0.105`
+
+### Interpretation
+
+- Question (1) is still open because the existing synthetic benchmark says little about engine-level serving.
+- Question (2) already has a partial answer: **yes, real downstream workloads can reach materially larger decode-only imbalance than the current "all-token whole-model" summary suggests**, especially on `vLLM`.
+- The dominant issue is not lack of measurements; it is that the current measurements are **not yet aligned to a decision metric**.
+
+## Ranked Ideas
+
+### 1. Trace-Grounded End-to-End CV Response Surface — RECOMMENDED
+
+**Thesis**: Build a metric-bridged study that measures how end-to-end `vLLM` serving changes as real routing traces are pushed from observed imbalance into higher imbalance, while keeping the engine, model, and request mix fixed.
+
+**Why this is the right first idea**
+
+- It directly answers both required questions.
+- It is `vLLM`-first and uses the code and measurement stack already present in:
+  - `scripts/export_layer_gpu_share_stats.py`
+  - `scripts/run_deepseek_v2_lite_vllm_longbench_multi.sh`
+  - `tests/kernels/moe/modular_kernel_tools/benchmark_eplb_multigpu.py`
+  - `scripts/run_moe_kernel_cv_sweep.py`
+- It turns the current ambiguity into a decision rule:
+  - if realistic or lightly stress-amplified traces never push whole-engine latency/throughput much, stop
+  - if decode-heavy imbalance explains meaningful slowdowns, proceed to an optimization phase
+
+**Pilot signal**: POSITIVE
+
+- Real workloads already show non-trivial decode-only imbalance.
+- Existing `EPLB` toggles can significantly change throughput, so the system is sensitive to the balancing mechanism even if the current metric story is inconsistent.
+- The single-layer kernel result being flat strengthens the case that the missing effect, if it exists, is an **engine interaction effect**, not just a kernel effect.
+
+**Novelty**: CONFIRMED AS A PRE-STUDY, NOT AS A NEW BALANCER
+
+- Closest prior work:
+  - `LLEP` asks whether inference workloads can be strongly imbalanced.
+  - `METRO` asks whether token balancing is the wrong objective in memory-bound serving.
+- Differentiation:
+  - this study does not propose a new router yet
+  - it determines whether `vLLM` `DeepSeek-V2-Lite` matrix4 actually enters the regimes assumed by those papers
+  - it focuses on trace-grounded metric reconciliation and causal end-to-end response, which is missing from the current local evidence
+
+**Reviewer score**: 8/10
+
+**Next step**: implement the experiment plan in `refine-logs/EXPERIMENT_PLAN.md`
+
+### 2. Decode-Centric Activated-Expert Study — BACKUP
+
+**Thesis**: Skip "all-token CV" as the primary lens and focus only on decode-phase imbalance, including activated-expert count and decode-step hot-rank concentration.
+
+**Why it is good**
+
+- Most aligned with `METRO`.
+- Supported by current local evidence: decode-only CV is much larger than all-token CV.
+
+**Why it is not first**
+
+- Too easy to become metric shopping if not tied back to end-to-end serving impact.
+- Still needs the broader trace-grounded study as a wrapper.
+
+### 3. Workload Frontier Mining — BACKUP
+
+**Thesis**: Expand from `multifieldqa_en` and `2wikimqa` into a workload frontier over `qasper`, `triviaqa`, `LEval`, `LongBench-v2`, `ShareGPT`, and scheduler stressors to find the highest realistic imbalance regimes.
+
+**Why it is good**
+
+- Strong answer to question (2).
+- Low risk and uses existing traces.
+
+**Why it is not first**
+
+- Alone it still does not answer question (1), which is about end-to-end impact.
+
+## Eliminated Ideas
+
+### Pure Kernel-CV Sweep Extension — ELIMINATED
+
+Reason: the existing single-layer synthetic sweep is already nearly flat from CV `0.05` to `0.20`. Repeating that with a few more points is unlikely to resolve the engine-level question.
+
+### Tune `EPLB` Hyperparameters First — ELIMINATED
+
+Reason: current evidence is too metric-sensitive. Tuning before deciding the primary objective risks optimizing the wrong target.
+
+### Training-Side Router Modification for DeepSeek-V2-Lite — ELIMINATED
+
+Reason: not `vLLM`-first and far outside the minimum-study scope.
+
+## Reviewer-Style Critical Feedback
+
+- The proposed study can easily collapse into a descriptive report with no decision power. It needs a pre-registered primary metric and kill criteria.
+- The study must separate **routing imbalance**, **expert mapping**, **chunking policy**, and **decode/prefill mix**. Otherwise any positive result will be unconvincing.
+- `EPLB` harming throughput today is not yet evidence against load balancing. It may be evidence that the current policy or its objective is mismatched to the serving regime.
+- Realism is the main risk. If the only way to reach high CV is unrealistic request synchronization or synthetic trace surgery, then optimization headroom for production may be weak.
+
+## Refined Proposal
+
+- Proposal: `refine-logs/FINAL_PROPOSAL.md`
+- Experiment plan: `refine-logs/EXPERIMENT_PLAN.md`
+- Tracker: `refine-logs/EXPERIMENT_TRACKER.md`
+
+## Next Steps
+
+- [ ] Run the metric-bridge audit across more existing workloads
+- [ ] Build the trace-amplification harness that perturbs real traces toward higher CV without changing the model
+- [ ] Launch the first three end-to-end runs listed in `refine-logs/EXPERIMENT_PLAN.md`
+- [ ] If the response curve is flat, stop
