new file mode 100644
index 000000000..c642965fc
--- /dev/null
+++ b/refine-logs/FINAL_PROPOSAL.md
@@ -0,0 +1,89 @@
+# Final Proposal
+
+## Problem Anchor
+
+Determine whether `vLLM` on `DeepSeek-V2-Lite` matrix4 has actionable load-balancing optimization headroom by measuring the **end-to-end response** to realistic and stress-amplified MoE routing imbalance.
+
+## Why This Problem, Not a Bigger One
+
+- The current evidence is contradictory across metrics.
+- The current kernel benchmark does not show a slowdown as CV increases.
+- Real traces already show larger decode-only imbalance than the all-token story suggests.
+- A new balancing algorithm is unjustified until these facts are reconciled inside the real engine.
+
+## Method Thesis
+
+Use a **trace-grounded metric bridge**:
+
+1. Measure the same run under three imbalance summaries:
+   - weighted per-layer CV
+   - whole-model weighted CV
+   - decode-only whole-model CV
+2. Mine the current workload frontier to find the highest realistic imbalance already present.
+3. Perturb real traces or request schedules to raise imbalance while preserving model, prompts, and serving stack.
+4. Fit an end-to-end response curve from imbalance to:
+   - throughput
+   - TTFT
+   - TPOT
+   - max-rank step time
+5. Use a stop/go rule:
+   - if the curve is flat in the realistic regime, stop
+   - if decode-heavy imbalance predicts worse serving, proceed to optimization
+
+## Dominant Contribution
+
+This is a **decision-quality systems pre-study**, not a new load balancer. Its contribution is to determine whether `vLLM` is in the same imbalance regime assumed by recent MoE serving work, and if so which imbalance objective matters operationally.
+
+## Scope
+
+### In scope
+
+- `vLLM` `DeepSeek-V2-Lite` matrix4
+- Existing LongBench and related downstream traces already present locally
+- Existing MoE recorder outputs and kernel CV tooling
+- Existing `EPLB` toggle and settings
+
+### Out of scope
+
+- Training-side router redesign
+- New expert kernels
+- Generalizing to all MoE models before this stack is understood
+
+## Primary Claims to Validate
+
+### Claim A
+
+Whole-engine serving is sensitive to routing imbalance in ways not revealed by the current single-layer synthetic kernel benchmark.
+
+### Claim B
+
+Real downstream workloads can reach imbalance regimes that are large enough, especially in decode, to expose that sensitivity.
+
+### Claim C
+
+The correct optimization target for this stack is more likely **decode-centric engine imbalance** than a generic all-token per-layer token-share summary.
+
+## Decision Rule
+
+Proceed to follow-on optimization only if all three hold:
+
+- realistic or lightly amplified traces exceed a pre-registered imbalance threshold
+- end-to-end latency or throughput degrades materially in that regime
+- the degradation is reproducible across at least two downstream workloads
+
+Otherwise stop and document that headroom is weak.
+
+## Minimum Success Standard
+
+- One primary metric chosen before the final conclusion
+- One realistic imbalance frontier table
+- One causal response curve
+- One stop/go recommendation that the team can defend
+
+## Expected Outcome
+
+The most likely outcome is not "EPLB is bad" or "load balancing is useless". The most likely outcome is:
+
+- the current summary metric is partially misleading
+- decode-heavy imbalance matters more than all-token imbalance
+- some workloads show genuine headroom, but only in a narrower regime than a kernel-only benchmark suggests
